<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1441,547,731]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,355,547,571]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Description</emphasis>
. Size large, length 3.0 to 5.0 mm. Clypeal apex straight, smooth, angled posteriorly (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 2" captionStartId="57.[192,287,1645,1667]" captionTargetBox="[209,1420,212,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-16@57.[192,1440,192,1637]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figures 2A-2H. Glaresis ecostata Fall. A) Habitus view. B) Clypeus and head surface. C) Pronotal surface. D) Metasternum and mesotibia. E) Elytral striae. F) Male genitalia. G) Metaleg and trochanter, dorsal view. H) Metaleg and trochanter, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4645619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4645619/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Pronotal fovea completely lacking (
<figureCitation box="[671,761,579,603]" captionStart="Figures 2" captionStartId="57.[192,287,1645,1667]" captionTargetBox="[209,1420,212,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-16@57.[192,1440,192,1637]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figures 2A-2H. Glaresis ecostata Fall. A) Habitus view. B) Clypeus and head surface. C) Pronotal surface. D) Metasternum and mesotibia. E) Elytral striae. F) Male genitalia. G) Metaleg and trochanter, dorsal view. H) Metaleg and trochanter, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4645619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4645619/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Elytral striae flat or weakly convex. Metasternum with surface ridges unmodified (
<figureCitation box="[522,616,611,635]" captionStart="Figures 2" captionStartId="57.[192,287,1645,1667]" captionTargetBox="[209,1420,212,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-16@57.[192,1440,192,1637]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figures 2A-2H. Glaresis ecostata Fall. A) Habitus view. B) Clypeus and head surface. C) Pronotal surface. D) Metasternum and mesotibia. E) Elytral striae. F) Male genitalia. G) Metaleg and trochanter, dorsal view. H) Metaleg and trochanter, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4645619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4645619/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Metatasternal surface with ridges unmodified. Metasternal groove absent. Mesotibia with about 5 spines on outer margin, mesotibial apex not produced; posterior metatrochanteral margin tridentate (
<figureCitation box="[644,733,675,699]" captionStart="Figures 3" captionStartId="58.[192,287,1665,1687]" captionTargetBox="[187,1399,224,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-18@58.[172,1441,192,1655]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="Figures 3A-3G. Glaresis bajaensis, new species. A) Habitus view. B) Clypeus and head surface. 3C) Pronotal surface. D) Metasternum and mesotibia. E) Elytral striae. F) Metaleg and trochanter, dorsal view. G) Metaleg and trochanter, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4645625" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4645625/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
). Metatibia deeply incised apically on inner and outer margins (
<figureCitation box="[258,353,707,731]" captionStart="Figures 2" captionStartId="57.[192,287,1645,1667]" captionTargetBox="[209,1420,212,1617]" captionTargetId="figure-16@57.[192,1440,192,1637]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figures 2A-2H. Glaresis ecostata Fall. A) Habitus view. B) Clypeus and head surface. C) Pronotal surface. D) Metasternum and mesotibia. E) Elytral striae. F) Male genitalia. G) Metaleg and trochanter, dorsal view. H) Metaleg and trochanter, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4645619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4645619/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
). Apex of 5th abdominal ventrite truncate in both sexes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1440,771,828]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,315,771,795]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Remarks</emphasis>
. The ecostata group contains 3 species and is the most easily recognized group within the genus.
</paragraph>
